g.text: Hydrogen is being used for a number of processes on earth today. The most common uses include fossil fuel processing and the production of ammonia, which is used for fertilizer. Hydrogen is also a potential clean fuel source.

Hydrogen is involved in the production of water molecules. Water molecules are attracted due to a unique bond, called hydrogen bonds. Hydrogen bonds are weak interactions between a hydrogen with a partial positive charge and an electronegative atom, such as oxygen.
Hydrogen is a gas at standard temperatures and pressures. It is colorless, odorless, tasteless, non-toxic, and nonmetallic. But it is also highly combustible!

Hydrogen, with a symbol of H, is the first element on the periodic table. It has an atomic number of 1, meaning that each hydrogen atom contains only one proton in its nucleus. It’s atomic weight, 1.00794 amu, makes it the lightest element there is. However, don’t underestimate the small and simple qualities of this element!

Hydrogen plays a essential role in the lives of the sun and other stars. During a process called nuclear fusion, hydrogen combines to form helium. This reaction releases an immense amount of energy. This energy fuels the stars, preventing them from collapsing and giving them their shine.
Hydrogen is the most abundant element in the universe. In fact, hydrogen and helium make up approximately 99.9% of the universe’s matter.
